Here's a simple C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word in the file:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::string targetWord, word;
    int count = 0;

    // Read the target word from user input
    std::cout << "Enter the target word: ";
    std::cin >> targetWord;

    // Open the input file
    std::ifstream inputFile("input.txt");

    // Check if the file is open, and display an error message if not
    if (!inputFile.is_open()) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening the file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    // Read the file line by line
    while (std::getline(inputFile, word)) {
        // Find the target word in the current line
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = word.find(targetWord, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
            ++count; // Increment the counter when found
            pos += targetWord.length(); // Move the search position forward
        }
    }

    // Close the input file
    inputFile.close();

    // Display the result
    std::cout << "The word '" << targetWord << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

To use this program, create a text file named `input.txt` in the same directory as your compiled C++ program. Then compile and run the program. When prompted, enter the target word you want to search for in the text file. The program will then display the number of occurrences of the target word in the file.

Please note that this program is case-sensitive and does not handle punctuation marks. You can modify the program to handle these cases according to your requirements.

